import java.util.LinkedList;
import java.util.Queue;
class RecentCounter {
    private Queue<Integer> requests;
    public RecentCounter(){
        requests = new LinkedList<>();
    }
    public int ping(int t) {
        requests.add(t);
        // Step 2: Remove all timestamps that are older than t - 3000
        while (!requests.isEmpty() && requests.peek() < t - 3000) 
            requests.poll();
        // Step 3: The remaining items in the queue are within the [t - 3000, t] range
        return requests.size();
    }
}

Time Complexity: O(1) amortized per ping call. While a single ping might trigger a while loop that removes 
multiple elements, each timestamp is added to the queue exactly once and removed from the queue at most once 
across the entire lifecycle of the stream.
Space Complexity: O(W), where W is the maximum number of requests that can arrive within a 3000 ms window. In the 
worst-case scenario given by the problem constraints, the queue will hold at most 3001 elements.

